A practical playbook for the JavaScript questions that actually decide your interview — closures, this, the event loop, async, and the traps that catch good engineers off guard.
Press enter or click to view image in full size

Here’s a question I’ve asked dozens of candidates: “What logs, and why?”
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 0);
}The candidates who say “0, 1, 2” fail. The ones who say “3, 3, 3” pass the first filter. The ones who can explain it — and then fix it two ways — are the ones who get the offer.
Most people don’t fail JavaScript interviews because they can’t code. They fail because they memorized syntax instead of understanding the model underneath. This playbook walks the five areas that decide the result, in the order they actually come up.
1. Closures — the question behind half the questions
That setTimeout loop is a closure question in disguise. var is function-scoped, so all three callbacks close over the same i. By the time they run (after the synchronous loop finishes), i is 3.
Two fixes, and you should know both:
// Fix 1: block scope — each iteration gets a fresh binding
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
setTimeout(() => console.log(i), 0); // 0, 1, 2
}// Fix 2: capture per-iteration value with an IIFE (the pre-ES6 way)
for (var i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
((j) => setTimeout(() => console.log(j), 0))(i); // 0, 1, 2
}When you say “let creates a new binding per iteration," you've shown you understand scope, not just a trick. That's the signal interviewers are listening for.
A closure is just a function holding a live reference to the variables in the scope where it was defined. The classic follow-up is a counter:
function makeCounter() {
let count = 0;
return () => ++count;
}
const next = makeCounter();
next(); // 1
next(); // 2 — count survives between callsIf you can articulate “the inner function keeps count alive after makeCounter returns," you're done with this section.
2. this — bind the rule to the call site, not the function
The mistake candidates make is asking “what is this here?" while staring at where a function is defined. this is decided by how a function is called. Memorize these four rules:

• Default: a plain fn() call → this is undefined in strict mode (or the global object otherwise).

• Implicit: obj.fn() → this is obj.

• Explicit: fn.call(x), fn.apply(x), fn.bind(x) → this is x.

• Arrow: no own this — it inherits from the enclosing lexical scope.
The trap they love:
const user = {
name: "Ada",
greet() {
return ["hi"].map(function () {
return `${this.name}`; // `this` is NOT user here
});
},
};The inner function is called by map with no owner, so this.name breaks. Switch to an arrow function and it inherits user:
greet() {
return ["hi"].map(() => `${this.name}`); // "Ada"
}Say why and you’ve nailed it: arrow functions don’t get their own this.
3. The event loop — sync, microtasks, then macrotasks
This is the single most predictive question. Give the model wrong and everything async you say afterward sounds shaky.
console.log("A");
setTimeout(() => console.log("B"), 0);
Promise.resolve().then(() => console.log("C"));
console.log("D");The answer is A, D, C, B. The order is the whole point:

• The call stack runs all synchronous code first → A, D.

• The microtask queue (Promise callbacks, queueMicrotask) drains completely before any timer → C.

• Only then do macrotasks (setTimeout, setInterval, I/O) run → B.
The rule to recite: after each task, the engine empties the entire microtask queue before picking up the next macrotask. That one sentence answers a dozen follow-ups.
4. Async/await — it’s promises with better ergonomics
Interviewers want to see that you know await doesn't block the thread — it suspends the function and hands control back to the event loop. Two things separate strong answers here.
Parallel vs sequential. This is a real performance bug, not a trivia question:
// Sequential — 600ms total. Usually wrong.
const a = await fetchA(); // 300ms
const b = await fetchB(); // 300ms// Parallel — 300ms total. Usually what you want.
const [a, b] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB()]);Error handling. A rejected promise inside async becomes a thrown error you catch with try/catch. If you're juggling several promises and need fine-grained control over which resolved and which failed, that's where the broader toolkit comes in — I cover the full set in the JavaScript Promise patterns for interviews breakdown, which is worth pairing with this one.
5. The traps that quietly fail you
A scattered list, because that’s how they show up in real interviews:

• typeof null === "object" — a historical bug in the language, not a mistake of yours. Know it.

• 0.1 + 0.2 !== 0.3 — IEEE-754 floating point. Compare with an epsilon, never ===.

• == vs === — == coerces ("" == 0 is true). Use === and explain coercion when asked.

• Reference vs value — objects and arrays are passed by reference; mutating an argument mutates the caller’s data.

• Hoisting — function declarations hoist fully; var hoists as undefined; let/const sit in the temporal dead zone and throw if accessed early.
You don’t need to memorize a hundred of these. You need the model — scope, the call site, the event loop — so you can derive the answer live when they hand you a snippet you’ve never seen.
How to prepare so it sticks
Stop reading explanations and start predicting outputs. Take any snippet, write down what you think logs, then run it. Every miss is a hole in your mental model — patch that hole, don’t just memorize the answer. After the JavaScript core, the next layer interviewers probe is React, and a surprising amount of it hinges on understanding identity and refs — see why useRef is more than a DOM escape hatch once you've got the fundamentals down.

